  "response": "Aging can significantly affect the EEG (electroencephalogram) power spectrum when a person is alert. Here are some key changes:\n\n1. Reduced Alpha Power\n- Decreased alpha wave (8-12 Hz) amplitude and power\n- Reduced alpha frequency peak\n- Slower alpha rhythm\n\n2. Increased Theta Power\n- Higher theta wave (4-8 Hz) activity\n- More prominent in frontal and prefrontal regions\n- Associated with cognitive slowing\n\n3. Decreased Beta Power\n- Reduced high-frequency beta activity (13-30 Hz)\n- Less cognitive processing speed and efficiency\n\n4. Spectral Complexity Changes\n- Decreased overall spectral entropy\n- Reduced complexity of neural oscillations\n- Less dynamic brain network interactions\n\n5. Regional Variations\n- Frontal regions show more pronounced changes\n- Posterior brain regions may be less affected\n\n6. Functional Implications\n- Reflects age-related cognitive decline\n- Correlates with reduced neuroplasticity\n- Indicates reduced neural synchronization\n\nThese changes reflect underlying neurological modifications like neuronal loss, reduced synaptic connectivity, and decreased metabolic efficiency associated with normal aging processes.",
